defaultThe Coastal Communities 2150 project helps 
defaultcommunities to 
defaultdevelop visions for 
defaultmanaging their long term risks from coastal
default and climate change to
default 2150 and beyond. The project is a partnership between the Environment Agency, Kent and Hampshire County Councils and partners in Belgium and Holland. It is funded by the European INTERREG bo
defaultdy.
default21.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Environment Agency is working in Newhaven, Seaford and Lewes in East Sussex, and has developed successful local engagement groups that are supported by town and parish councils. Kent County Council is working in Margate, the Isle Sheppey and the Ro
defaultmney Marshes. Hampshire County Council is engaging at 6 sites around the Solent.  
default22.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPublic interest has been higher than expected and is driven by the desire to shape long term community plans. The UK partners have found it easier to form local public engag
defaultement groups than the Dutch or Belgians, who have encountered a public attitude that ‘the government have always dealt with this - so why should I get involved?’
default23.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRecent extreme weather events such as the droughts and floods in 2012 and Hurricane Sandy in N
defaultew York seem to have contributed to general public acceptance that weather events have become more extreme and communities should prepare for more to come.
default 
defaultThe 150 year time frame has not been a problem for the public or businesses, who seem generally conc
defaulterned with leaving a sustainable legacy for future generations.
