default26.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMore expert audiences such as utilities are comfortable talking about climate change and appreciate to the need to adapt. However, they 
defaultare 
defaultalso primarily interested in the impacts of climate change rather than 
defaultthe climate itself. 
default 
defaultA lack of relevant information is often cited as a barrier to action, with organisations finding it difficult to translate climate projections into the more relevant impact assessments that they need to inform adaptation decisions. 
default27.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe
default have undertaken market surveys to understand how potential customers for our Climate Ready Support Service
default,
default 
defaultincluding
default 
defaultorganisations in the
default, business, local government, infrastructure, built environment, health, natural environ
defaultment, agriculture and 
defaultforestry sectors,
default 
defaultengage with climate adaptation, and what language resonates with them. In summary, this shows that:
default-
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOrganisations are more familiar with climate cha
defaultnge mitigation than adaptation 
defaultand are more likely to be acting to mitigate climate change
default.  The reasons for this include: greater understanding of how to act; actions are associated with cost savings; they can apply tangible, measurable, specific targets; and existing regulation.  By contrast adaptation tends to have a lower profile and is ass
defaultociated with more barriers to action.  
default-
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhen thinking specifically about environmental risks there is relatively high awareness of climate change among the target audience and organisations perceive it to be the top environmental risk (as important as envi
defaultronmental regulation/compliance).  Organisations also identify the impacts of climate change as key risks (e.g. flooding, droughts, heat-wave
defaults, 
defaultand extreme weather).  29%
default of organisations believe they have already been affected by climate change a great de
defaultal and a further 
default39% 
defaultbelieve that they have been affected a little. The target audience are most likely to think they will be affected by disruptions to staff (63%), 
defaultall
default 
defaultimpact on logistics (60%), and all
default impact on premises or infrastructure (58%).
default-
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe m
defaultaj
defaultority of organisations have
default a strategic approach 
defaultto 
defaultrisk management as part of their normal business planning, and so can manage climate risks within that process rather than separately.
default-
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOrganisations commonly cite barriers to adaptation that include: miti
defaultgation taking priority over adaptation; 
defaultshort-term focus is prioritised
default 
default(
defaultadaptation is perceived to be long-term); a lack of understanding of the business case (the financial argument); economic pressures; lack of knowledge, capacity, finances and time; la
defaultck of confidence in the science and difficulty dealing with probabilities.
default28.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt can also be effective to focus on adaptation actions (solutions) rather than climate (uncertain problems). In many cases, no- or low-regret actions can be taken that make sense r
defaultegardless of future climate. For example, businesses can benefit from simple water efficiency measures or registering for our flood warning service irrespective of how the climate changes.
